<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1902-03-06T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1902-03-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="46" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d46">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">McCormick</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-03-06"><hi rend="italic">March 6,
                                1902</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 35.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                            No. 67 of the 11th ultimo, in regard to the treatment to be accorded to
                            United States passports and their bearers in Austria-Hungary.</p>
                        <p>Your conduct of the matter, as reported in your despatch, has the
                            Department’s approval, as has the fifth article of the proposed
                            instruction to the Austro-Hungarian local authorities, requiring a
                            receipt from them in every case in which they deem it necessary
                            temporarily to take from an American citizen his passport.</p>
                        <p rend="center">* * * * * * *</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>